2. 🎯 Problem Statement

2.1 The Safety-Generalization Dichotomy

Contemporary robotics faces a fundamental tension between semantically rich but unverifiable learning-based methods and provably safe but semantically blind classical control. This gap is particularly acute in the context of Vision-Language-Action (VLA) foundation models, which achieve remarkable generalization but offer no stability guarantees.

Paradigm Strengths Weaknesses
Classical Control (MPC, LQR, CBF) Formal safety/stability proofs No semantic understanding, poor generalization
Foundation Models (RT-2, OpenVLA, Diffusion Policy successors) Rich semantic grounding, few-shot generalization Black-box, no certificates, computational intractability
Geometric Deep Learning (SE(3)-Transformers, Tensor Field Networks) Exploits symmetry, data-efficient Typically static, not integrated with control

The Gap: No existing framework simultaneously provides:

· Formal certificates (Lyapunov stability, barrier functions)
· Semantic reasoning (language grounding, task composition)
· Computational efficiency (sparse, O(N) scaling)
· Symmetry awareness (equivariance to rotations/translations)

2.2 The Computational Bottleneck

Transformer-based policies scale quadratically with context length. Biological brains achieve remarkable efficiency through sparse, dynamic connectivity—only 1-2% of neurons are active at any moment. This inspires the need for a dynamic graph architecture that activates only relevant cognitive sub-networks based on task demands.

2.3 Research Questions

Primary: Can we formulate robotic cognition as a switching dynamical system on a time-varying graph such that:

· (RQ1) The system is contracting (exponentially stable) despite arbitrary topology changes driven by task and attention?
· (RQ2) Safety constraints are guaranteed via barrier functions that interact with learned components, even under model uncertainty?
· (RQ3) The resulting architecture achieves sparse computation (O(N) complexity) without sacrificing representational power?

Secondary: Does imposing SE(3)-equivariance throughout the pipeline (perception → cognition → action) enable zero-shot generalization to novel object configurations as a mathematical consequence?

